00:24:30.600 --> 00:24:32.650
not get to go on the Today Show,
because I write literary

00:24:32.650 --> 00:24:36.250
fiction that doesn't contain
vampires or, like, love

00:24:36.250 --> 00:24:38.430
stories for the ages or
anything like that.

00:24:38.430 --> 00:24:42.640
But, like, with this one, it
was just a little cute book

00:24:42.640 --> 00:24:44.860
that I wrote kind
of as a joke.

00:24:44.860 --> 00:24:47.420
But it turned out that every
parent in the world feels the

00:24:47.420 --> 00:24:49.390
way that I did.

00:24:49.390 --> 00:24:51.400
It's funny, because the book
barely got published.

00:24:51.400 --> 00:24:53.520
I barely even attempted
to publish it.

00:24:53.520 --> 00:24:56.600
I wrote it, I read it at dinner
parties for a couple of

00:24:56.600 --> 00:24:59.300
months, and then I sent it to
my friend who runs a very

00:24:59.300 --> 00:25:02.750
small independent publishing
house in Brooklyn, has a

00:25:02.750 --> 00:25:03.500
couple of kids.

00:25:03.500 --> 00:25:04.380
I knew they didn't sleep.

00:25:04.380 --> 00:25:06.390
I thought he might think
it was funny.

00:25:06.390 --> 00:25:09.410
And there was this strange
moment where we both thought

00:25:09.410 --> 00:25:12.520
the book was really funny, and
yet neither of us was really

00:25:12.520 --> 00:25:14.640
ready to pull the trigger
and publish it.

00:25:14.640 --> 00:25:17.900
We thought we might just be
bad parents, you know?

00:25:17.900 --> 00:25:21.950
And then even after he decided
that he would publish it, we

00:25:21.950 --> 00:25:23.800
had all these conundrums,
all these problems.

00:25:23.800 --> 00:25:27.230
We didn't know simple stuff,
like where the bookstore would

00:25:27.230 --> 00:25:28.680
this book be stocked?

00:25:28.680 --> 00:25:30.620
We were clear that the
children's section was

00:25:30.620 --> 00:25:33.870
inappropriate, in that it
says fuck on the cover.

00:25:33.870 --> 00:25:34.900
But we didn't, like--

00:25:34.900 --> 00:25:35.620
was it humor?

00:25:35.620 --> 00:25:36.540
Is it this?

00:25:36.540 --> 00:25:39.710
And this was resolved one day
when Johnny, my publisher,

00:25:39.710 --> 00:25:42.350
walked into his local
independent bookstore and

00:25:42.350 --> 00:25:44.200
presented the book to them,
and asked them where they

00:25:44.200 --> 00:25:45.400
would stock it.

00:25:45.400 --> 00:25:46.920
And they read it, and they
laughed, and they were like,

00:25:46.920 --> 00:25:47.810
oh, this is perfect.

00:25:47.810 --> 00:25:50.230
This goes in the parenting
section.

00:25:50.230 --> 00:25:54.050
And me and Johnny were like,
there's a parenting section?

00:25:54.050 --> 00:25:56.480
Which confirms the earlier
thesis about us being shitty

00:25:56.480 --> 00:25:58.650
parents, I guess.

00:25:58.650 --> 00:26:00.810
But yeah, like, on the Today
Show, I went on a couple

00:26:00.810 --> 00:26:04.310
times, and once they knew who
I was, and once they didn't.

00:26:04.310 --> 00:26:07.070
And the first time I was on
there with Matt Lauer, right?

00:26:07.070 --> 00:26:08.440
Real stand up guy.

00:26:08.440 --> 00:26:09.380
Very, very nice.

00:26:09.380 --> 00:26:11.260
There's a real art to
interviewing people,

00:26:11.260 --> 00:26:14.400
especially in a fraught
situation like live national

00:26:14.400 --> 00:26:15.400
television.

00:26:15.400 --> 00:26:17.910
Everybody's nervous, it's real
early in the morning, you're

00:26:17.910 --> 00:26:20.690
heavily caffeinated, and you're
in front of a plate

00:26:20.690 --> 00:26:22.900
glass window, and all these
people are, like, behind it

00:26:22.900 --> 00:26:25.860
holding up signs that they made
that morning at their

00:26:25.860 --> 00:26:27.270
hotels or whatever.

00:26:27.270 --> 00:26:28.670
I don't know what the hell
they're doing there.

00:26:28.670 --> 00:26:31.730
But like, I don't know if
they're from the Kalamazoo,

00:26:31.730 --> 00:26:33.670
Michigan Board of Tourism or
whatever, because they're

00:26:33.670 --> 00:26:34.780
behind, they're like, aah!

00:26:34.780 --> 00:26:35.960
Kalamazoo!

00:26:35.960 --> 00:26:38.980
It's like, you came to New York
to stand here at 6:45 in

00:26:38.980 --> 00:26:41.430
the morning with a sign
that says Kalamazoo?

00:26:41.430 --> 00:26:42.080
Really?

00:26:42.080 --> 00:26:43.890
That's your idea
of a vacation?

00:26:43.890 --> 00:26:47.940
Anyway, so Matt Lauer has like
two minutes before you go live

00:26:47.940 --> 00:26:49.870
on air to make you
feel comfortable.

00:26:49.870 --> 00:26:51.090
And he's great at his job.

00:26:51.090 --> 00:26:54.070
By the time I went on with Matt
Lauer, I felt like we

00:26:54.070 --> 00:26:57.320
were old friends, and after the
interview, we were going

00:26:57.320 --> 00:27:01.690
to go eat some pancakes or
hit some golf balls.

00:27:01.690 --> 00:27:04.580
Whatever the fuck Matt Lauer
does for fun, you know?

00:27:04.580 --> 00:27:07.890
And we get on, and the first
thing he says is, Adam, before

00:27:07.890 --> 00:27:09.550
this book, you wrote
several novels.

00:27:09.550 --> 00:27:10.915
You're an award winning
novelist.

00:27:10.915 --> 00:27:12.990
And I was real grateful
for that.

00:27:12.990 --> 00:27:14.360
And the interview was cool.

00:27:14.360 --> 00:27:17.810
And then I came back two days
later to do the Today Show

00:27:17.810 --> 00:27:21.230
again, with Kathie
Lee Gifford.

00:27:21.230 --> 00:27:23.220
It's a very different
situation.

00:27:23.220 --> 00:27:26.280
Everybody referred to this as
the 11:00 hour, which sounded

00:27:26.280 --> 00:27:27.000
really ominous.

00:27:27.000 --> 00:27:29.060
I didn't know what that means.

00:27:29.060 --> 00:27:31.370
In retrospect, it means that
Kathie Lee Gifford starts

00:27:31.370 --> 00:27:34.100
drinking at 10:00.

00:27:34.100 --> 00:27:37.630
And like, again, two minutes
to make me feel comfortable

00:27:37.630 --> 00:27:38.810
before we go on air.

00:27:38.810 --> 00:27:41.920
The last thing Kathie Lee
Gifford says to me before the

00:27:41.920 --> 00:27:44.590
cameras roll and we're live
to however many million

00:27:44.590 --> 00:27:46.780
households is, your
daughter Vivian.

00:27:46.780 --> 00:27:49.650
How old is she, that
little bitch?

00:27:49.650 --> 00:27:52.540
I was like, really, Kathie
Lee Gifford?

00:27:52.540 --> 00:27:55.420
I will punch you in your face
on live television.

00:27:55.420 --> 00:27:58.070
Like, I know I wrote a book with
curse words in it, but

00:27:58.070 --> 00:27:59.600
yo, for real, Kathie
Lee Gifford?

00:27:59.600 --> 00:28:00.880
So I was like, totally
flustered

00:28:00.880 --> 00:28:02.090
when the cameras rolled.

00:28:02.090 --> 00:28:04.340
I didn't know what
was going on.

00:28:04.340 --> 00:28:05.000
It was crazy.

00:28:05.000 --> 00:28:08.530
So, sometimes weird
things happen.

00:28:08.530 --> 00:28:10.630
And a lot of weird things
happened with this book.

00:28:10.630 --> 00:28:13.920
Among other things, people
often got the mistaken

00:28:13.920 --> 00:28:15.400
impression that I
am a parenting

00:28:15.400 --> 00:28:16.650
expert or a sleep guru.

00:28:19.700 --> 00:28:21.960
People also got the impression
that this was

00:28:21.960 --> 00:28:23.170
a children's book.

00:28:23.170 --> 00:28:26.480
Like, people were up in arms on
the interwebs talking about

00:28:26.480 --> 00:28:29.850
how they would never read
this book to a child.

00:28:29.850 --> 00:28:33.180
It seems to me that it would
take a startling unique blend

00:28:33.180 --> 00:28:37.610
of literacy and illiteracy to
mistakenly read this book to a

00:28:37.610 --> 00:28:40.280
child, in that it says
fuck on the cover.

00:28:40.280 --> 00:28:41.530
Again, I'll come back to that.

00:28:44.500 --> 00:28:47.710
One of the incidents that was,
to me, the funniest was, I was

00:28:47.710 --> 00:28:51.530
asked to be a co-host
at a charity event.

00:28:51.530 --> 00:28:54.100
A fundraiser for a Boston
children's hospital.

00:28:54.100 --> 00:28:57.270
I'm from Boston, but the event
was in LA, because presumably,

00:28:57.270 --> 00:28:59.080
people in LA have
a lot of money.

00:28:59.080 --> 00:29:01.110
So the co-host--

00:29:01.110 --> 00:29:04.070
my co-host at the event was
this guy, Doctor Richard

00:29:04.070 --> 00:29:06.260
Ferber, who may be familiar
to some of

00:29:06.260 --> 00:29:07.340
you if you have children.

00:29:07.340 --> 00:29:09.070
Who has kids in this audience?

00:29:09.070 --> 00:29:10.240
OK.

00:29:10.240 --> 00:29:11.660
Richard Ferber-- that
ring a bell?

00:29:11.660 --> 00:29:13.690
The Ferber Method?

00:29:13.690 --> 00:29:15.310
Sleep training?

00:29:15.310 --> 00:29:17.890
He's regarded by some
as a monster, and

00:29:17.890 --> 00:29:19.020
by others as a hero.

00:29:19.020 --> 00:29:20.480
He's a titan of the field.

00:29:20.480 --> 00:29:21.840
His theory is basically
that you should let

00:29:21.840 --> 00:29:22.750
your kid cry it out.

00:29:22.750 --> 00:29:24.310
It's the opposite
of what we would

00:29:24.310 --> 00:29:27.230
call attachment parenting.

00:29:27.230 --> 00:29:30.520
Among those who find his work
controversial and monstrous is

00:29:30.520 --> 00:29:33.732
my wife Victoria, who was
accompanying me to the event.

00:29:33.732 --> 00:29:36.550
And I was seriously afraid that
she was going to, like,

00:29:36.550 --> 00:29:40.070
throw a drink in his face or
something, because that theory

00:29:40.070 --> 00:29:43.950
of letting your kid scream and
cry until they fall asleep,

00:29:43.950 --> 00:29:47.260
and thus freeing yourself from
the type of situation you deal

00:29:47.260 --> 00:29:51.160
with if you don't, she could
never really wrap her mind

00:29:51.160 --> 00:29:51.580
around that.

00:29:51.580 --> 00:29:54.260
So I was worried about that.

00:29:54.260 --> 00:29:57.600
Doctor Ferber had requested
some slides from the book.

00:29:57.600 --> 00:30:00.690
Some images from the book to
use in his presentation.

00:30:00.690 --> 00:30:02.010
I was not giving
a presentation.

00:30:02.010 --> 00:30:05.180
My job was to drink
and shake hands.

00:30:05.180 --> 00:30:07.540
I'm a titan when it comes to
drinking and shaking hands.

00:30:07.540 --> 00:30:09.120
I'm great at that.

00:30:09.120 --> 00:30:12.180
And like, it was totally
inappropriate for him to give

00:30:12.180 --> 00:30:15.180
a presentation, because these
were a bunch of decadent, rich

00:30:15.180 --> 00:30:19.060
LA people who didn't need a 20
minute slide show about how to

00:30:19.060 --> 00:30:22.610
put your kids to bed, because
they have nannies who do that.

00:30:22.610 --> 00:30:24.600
So he's giving this long
presentation, and when he

00:30:24.600 --> 00:30:28.240
finally gets around to the
images from the book, the one

00:30:28.240 --> 00:30:31.500
that he shows is an
image of a father.

00:30:31.500 --> 00:30:34.020
And this illustration is based
on me, because my Illustrator

00:30:34.020 --> 00:30:35.990
Ricardo works from
photographs.

00:30:35.990 --> 00:30:38.140
A guy who looks something
like me, sneaking out

00:30:38.140 --> 00:30:40.890
of the kid's room.

00:30:40.890 --> 00:30:42.760
The verse goes like this.

00:30:42.760 --> 00:30:47.160
Bleary and dazed, I awaken to
find your eyes shut, so I keep

00:30:47.160 --> 00:30:51.060
my fingers crossed tight as I
tiptoe away and pray that

00:30:51.060 --> 00:30:53.450
you're fucking asleep.

00:30:53.450 --> 00:30:54.540
And he put it on the screen.

00:30:54.540 --> 00:30:57.000
He was like, this is what
you should never do.

00:30:57.000 --> 00:30:58.010
I was like, really, Doc?

00:30:58.010 --> 00:30:59.170
You just threw me
under the sleep

00:30:59.170 --> 00:31:00.930
training bus, Dr. Ferber?

00:31:00.930 --> 00:31:03.750
And it was kind of wild.

00:31:03.750 --> 00:31:08.020
I was standing in the back,
imbibing, you know?

00:31:08.020 --> 00:31:10.850
But the crazy part is that the
next morning, I get an email

00:31:10.850 --> 00:31:12.510
from Dr. Ferber.

00:31:12.510 --> 00:31:14.380
And the email-- we're staying
in the same hotel.

00:31:14.380 --> 00:31:16.560
He could have just knocked
on my door.

00:31:16.560 --> 00:31:20.250
And the email says, why didn't
you tell me that I know you?

00:31:20.250 --> 00:31:24.070
I'm like, Dr. Ferber
has lost his mind.

00:31:24.070 --> 00:31:27.490
And it turns out that I
went to summer camp--

00:31:27.490 --> 00:31:30.990
before I got kicked out, which
is a separate story.

00:31:30.990 --> 00:31:32.320
I used to get kicked out
of a lot of things.

00:31:32.320 --> 00:31:35.530
Sunday school, summer camp.

00:31:35.530 --> 00:31:38.760
I went to summer camp with
his son, Thad Ferber.

00:31:38.760 --> 00:31:41.330
The unforgettably named
Thad Ferber.

00:31:41.330 --> 00:31:44.700
And when you're like 13, your
friends from summer camp who

00:31:44.700 --> 00:31:47.390
live two towns away, you see
them like, once during the

00:31:47.390 --> 00:31:48.230
school year.

00:31:48.230 --> 00:31:53.250
So when I was 13 in 1990, Thad
Ferber and I went to Tower

00:31:53.250 --> 00:31:55.250
Records on Newbury
Street in Boston.

00:31:55.250 --> 00:31:56.780
And I was a hip hop
kid, right?

00:31:56.780 --> 00:31:59.800
I was a rapper, I was a DJ,
which is why I'm writing

00:31:59.800 --> 00:32:01.740
novels about graffiti
these days.

00:32:01.740 --> 00:32:04.850
And so we went up to the top
floor to buy some rap records,

00:32:04.850 --> 00:32:07.960
and there was a big life size
cardboard cutout of MC Hammer

00:32:07.960 --> 00:32:11.140
up there, because MC Hammer,
from Oakland,

00:32:11.140 --> 00:32:13.370
was large in 1990.

00:32:13.370 --> 00:32:16.000
But he wasn't exactly the
purest of products.

00:32:16.000 --> 00:32:17.960
Those of us who were rap
purists had a real

00:32:17.960 --> 00:32:18.550
problem with him.

00:32:18.550 --> 00:32:20.170
We thought he was watering
down the music.

00:32:20.170 --> 00:32:21.920
He was at the top of
the pop charts.

00:32:21.920 --> 00:32:24.570
You may remember the large pants
he liked to dance in,

00:32:24.570 --> 00:32:27.210
and subsequently the Kentucky
Fried Chicken ads he starred

00:32:27.210 --> 00:32:31.280
in, followed by a long,
drawn out bankrupty.

00:32:31.280 --> 00:32:34.130
So naturally, I ripped the
head off the cardboard MC

00:32:34.130 --> 00:32:37.170
Hammer cutout and stuffed it in
my jacket, which was not an

00:32:37.170 --> 00:32:40.600
act of theft as much
as decapitation.

00:32:40.600 --> 00:32:44.460
And I attempted to exit the
store and was apprehended by

00:32:44.460 --> 00:32:47.270
security, in classic fashion,
trying to go through the

00:32:47.270 --> 00:32:50.870
revolving door, and they came
and put their foot and took me

00:32:50.870 --> 00:32:53.380
and Thad Ferber, who was guilty
by association, down to

00:32:53.380 --> 00:32:55.690
the dungeon beneath
Tower Records.

00:32:55.690 --> 00:32:59.890
And there, they browbeat us and
told us that the cardboard

00:32:59.890 --> 00:33:02.270
cutout cost like $8,000--

00:33:02.270 --> 00:33:05.060
which I find dubious--

00:33:05.060 --> 00:33:07.930
and he told me I was banned for
life from Tower Records,

00:33:07.930 --> 00:33:11.330
and they would only release me
into the custody of the police

00:33:11.330 --> 00:33:14.160
or my parents.

00:33:14.160 --> 00:33:16.720
So this was not my
first rodeo.

00:33:16.720 --> 00:33:17.820
I got in trouble quite a bit.

00:33:17.820 --> 00:33:21.350
So I had a phone number
memorized that was a fake

00:33:21.350 --> 00:33:23.020
number that just
rang and rang.

00:33:23.020 --> 00:33:25.200
So I gave them that number as
my parents' number, and it

00:33:25.200 --> 00:33:28.840
just rang and rang, and I was
like, I guess they're out.

00:33:28.840 --> 00:33:32.310
Thad Ferber had never been to
the rodeo before, so he gave

00:33:32.310 --> 00:33:33.980
them his parents' number.

00:33:33.980 --> 00:33:37.580
And in short order, Dr. Richard
Ferber showed up and

00:33:37.580 --> 00:33:38.450
took us both home.

00:33:38.450 --> 00:33:39.920
And I had totally forgot
about this.

00:33:39.920 --> 00:33:42.670
I had never connected Thad
Ferber to Richard Ferber, so

00:33:42.670 --> 00:33:44.750
my mind was blown.

00:33:44.750 --> 00:33:47.030
And it actually made me feel a
lot better about everything,

00:33:47.030 --> 00:33:49.950
because clearly, Dr. Ferber is
not that great of a fucking

00:33:49.950 --> 00:33:55.360
parent, in that he let his
son hang out with me.

00:33:55.360 --> 00:33:58.730
So that was one of the richer
anecdotes from the Go The Fuck

00:33:58.730 --> 00:34:00.950
To Sleep insanity.

00:34:00.950 --> 00:34:03.800
Also good was the time that they
tried to ban the book in

00:34:03.800 --> 00:34:06.180
New Zealand, of all
places, right?

00:34:06.180 --> 00:34:07.300
New Zealand.

00:34:07.300 --> 00:34:09.179
I think of New Zealanders,
Kiwis, as

00:34:09.179 --> 00:34:10.590
being fairly free spirited.

00:34:10.590 --> 00:34:13.060
But there's a group there--

00:34:13.060 --> 00:34:14.710
and in fairness, the censorship

00:34:14.710 --> 00:34:16.449
efforts never got anywhere.

00:34:16.449 --> 00:34:19.280
But it was this group called
Family First New Zealand.

00:34:19.280 --> 00:34:22.050
And the president of the
organization, who I think was

00:34:22.050 --> 00:34:24.750
also probably the vice
president, the sergeant at

00:34:24.750 --> 00:34:27.239
arms, the secretary,
you know--

00:34:27.239 --> 00:34:29.230
put out this press release,
which I thought was great.

00:34:29.230 --> 00:34:30.690
I have it framed in
my office now.

00:34:30.690 --> 00:34:36.000
And it said, while this book may
be amusing and harmless in

00:34:36.000 --> 00:34:39.750
the hands of normal, well
adjusted people, we are really

00:34:39.750 --> 00:34:42.610
worried about its effects in
the hands of aggressive,

00:34:42.610 --> 00:34:45.060
dysfunctional parents.

00:34:45.060 --> 00:34:47.370
I was like, that's the rubric
for what we ban now?

00:34:47.370 --> 00:34:49.699
What aggressive dysfunctional
people should

00:34:49.699 --> 00:34:50.949
not have access to?

00:34:50.949 --> 00:34:53.870
Do you also propose
to ban spoons?

00:34:53.870 --> 00:34:55.659
That could be a problem in
the hands of aggressive,

00:34:55.659 --> 00:34:58.270
dysfunctional people.

00:34:58.270 --> 00:35:00.900
Luckily for us, the audiobook,
which was read in this country

00:35:00.900 --> 00:35:04.920
by Samuel L Jackson, and also
Werner Herzog did a version

00:35:04.920 --> 00:35:05.510
for us as well.

00:35:05.510 --> 00:35:06.840
You should YouTube that one.

00:35:06.840 --> 00:35:09.320
Also an adorable Filipino
grandmother, whose version

00:35:09.320 --> 00:35:10.270
went viral on the interwebs.

00:35:10.270 --> 00:35:12.690
That's probably my favorite.

00:35:12.690 --> 00:35:15.020
In Australia and New Zealand,
the reader was this woman

00:35:15.020 --> 00:35:16.830
named Noni Hazlehurst.

00:35:16.830 --> 00:35:18.660
Anybody from that part
of the world in the

00:35:18.660 --> 00:35:19.910
building right now?

00:35:19.910 --> 00:35:20.060
Yeah?

00:35:20.060 --> 00:35:21.330
You know who Noni
Hazlehurst is?

00:35:21.330 --> 00:35:22.162
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:35:22.162 --> 00:35:23.370
ADAM MANSBACH: Yeah, she
was on Playschool.

00:35:23.370 --> 00:35:26.860
She's like Maria from Sesame
Street crossed with Meryl

00:35:26.860 --> 00:35:29.180
Streep for that part
of the world.

00:35:29.180 --> 00:35:32.820
She's like, a successful film
actor who also is a legendary

00:35:32.820 --> 00:35:35.340
child's television presenter.

00:35:35.340 --> 00:35:37.990
And when Family First New
Zealand came out with their

00:35:37.990 --> 00:35:41.380
objections, Noni Hazlehurst
went on national TV and

00:35:41.380 --> 00:35:44.400
basically told them to go fuck
themselves, and that was,

00:35:44.400 --> 00:35:46.340
like, the end of it.

00:35:46.340 --> 00:35:48.980
And that was an interesting
phenomenon here, too.

00:35:48.980 --> 00:35:51.340
Whenever somebody came out of
the woodwork and objected to

00:35:51.340 --> 00:35:55.400
the book in whatever way, the
grandmothers of America

00:35:55.400 --> 00:35:59.660
basically stepped in to our
defense and shut down

00:35:59.660 --> 00:36:00.190
everything.

00:36:00.190 --> 00:36:02.720
And they had, like, the ultimate
moral authority.

00:36:02.720 --> 00:36:05.110
And they turned out to be a
really hip and crass group of

00:36:05.110 --> 00:36:09.470
people, and I'm very
grateful to them.

00:36:09.470 --> 00:36:09.880
So yeah.

00:36:09.880 --> 00:36:13.110
I ended up talking nonstop
about this book for like,

00:36:13.110 --> 00:36:16.180
eight months, eight hours
a day, crazy amounts of

00:36:16.180 --> 00:36:17.020
interviews and stuff.

00:36:17.020 --> 00:36:20.940
And it's nice to have
a new novel out.

00:36:20.940 --> 00:36:23.310
And there is a connection, I
think, between the two books,

00:36:23.310 --> 00:36:26.460
in the sense that what I'm
interested in exploring in my

00:36:26.460 --> 00:36:31.020
work is sort of paradox
and human complexity.

00:36:31.020 --> 00:36:33.680
I think that's where narrative
and conflict come from.

00:36:33.680 --> 00:36:36.150
That's where good fiction
comes from.

00:36:36.150 --> 00:36:39.550
And that can be a very simple
paradox, like the paradox of

00:36:39.550 --> 00:36:42.710
loving your kid to death, but
also being willing to do

00:36:42.710 --> 00:36:45.110
anything in the world to get out
of that kid's room after

00:36:45.110 --> 00:36:49.080
an hour and a half of trying to
put that little creatures

00:36:49.080 --> 00:36:54.070
to bed, or it can be kind of
larger societal paradoxes.

00:36:54.070 --> 00:36:56.620
In this book, I'm dealing with
the world of graffiti.

00:36:56.620 --> 00:37:00.600
Subway graffiti as it originated
as a movement in

00:37:00.600 --> 00:37:02.500
New York City in the
'70s and '80s.

00:37:02.500 --> 00:37:05.060
It was controversial then,
it remains so now.

00:37:05.060 --> 00:37:07.760
But for me, the lives of
graffiti writers are

00:37:07.760 --> 00:37:09.870
fascinating, because
they embody so many

00:37:09.870 --> 00:37:11.840
tensions and paradoxes.

00:37:11.840 --> 00:37:15.850
They tend to be the eccentrics,
the mad geniuses,

00:37:15.850 --> 00:37:17.980
the theorists of hip hop.

00:37:17.980 --> 00:37:21.370
And I've enjoyed getting to
know them over the past 25

00:37:21.370 --> 00:37:23.620
years of my life.

00:37:23.620 --> 00:37:26.210
And the paradoxes that they have
to deal with are sort of

00:37:26.210 --> 00:37:29.095
the tension between fame
and anonymity.

00:37:29.095 --> 00:37:32.950
These guys are pursuing fame
in a brilliant and original

00:37:32.950 --> 00:37:34.200
fashion, right?

00:37:34.200 --> 00:37:37.470
The New York City subway trains
became their canvases.

00:37:37.470 --> 00:37:41.740
These were kids who were largely
disenfranchised,

00:37:41.740 --> 00:37:45.560
coming out of marginal living
conditions in the Bronx and

00:37:45.560 --> 00:37:47.690
Brooklyn, at a time when New
York City was bankrupt--

00:37:47.690 --> 00:37:51.360
at a time when art and music
programs had all but been

00:37:51.360 --> 00:37:52.900
destroyed in that city--

00:37:52.900 --> 00:37:55.760
at a time when--

00:37:55.760 --> 00:37:58.910
this is New York circa Ford
to New York drop dead.

00:37:58.910 --> 00:38:01.080
Jimmy Carter driving through the
Bronx, and getting out of

00:38:01.080 --> 00:38:03.260
his car, and frowning and
getting back in and

00:38:03.260 --> 00:38:05.020
disappearing.

00:38:05.020 --> 00:38:07.890
These kids figured out how to
make the subway trains of New

00:38:07.890 --> 00:38:10.450
York their personal canvases.

00:38:10.450 --> 00:38:12.110
They circulated through the
city, and were seen by

00:38:12.110 --> 00:38:13.510
millions of people a day.

00:38:13.510 --> 00:38:17.150
The city of New York spent $300
million between 1972 and

00:38:17.150 --> 00:38:20.420
1990 trying to win this
war against a bunch of

00:38:20.420 --> 00:38:21.670
15-year-olds.

00:38:21.670 --> 00:38:24.510
Those 15-year-olds outsmarted
them at every turn.

00:38:24.510 --> 00:38:26.950
And to me, there's always been
something epic and heroic

00:38:26.950 --> 00:38:28.870
about graffiti in
a certain sense.

00:38:28.870 --> 00:38:32.340
So there's that tension between
art and vandalism.

00:38:32.340 --> 00:38:34.650
Most graffiti writers view
their work as both, and

00:38:34.650 --> 00:38:36.970
they're not trying to privilege
one over the other.

00:38:36.970 --> 00:38:38.540
They see it as equally valuable

00:38:38.540 --> 00:38:40.270
for both those reasons.

00:38:40.270 --> 00:38:44.380
Fame and anonymity, art and
vandalism, beautifying and

00:38:44.380 --> 00:38:47.200
destroying a city.

00:38:47.200 --> 00:38:49.910
Even today, the war on graffiti,
although it's been

00:38:49.910 --> 00:38:51.740
successful in removing graffiti
from the subway

00:38:51.740 --> 00:38:53.240
trains, rages on.

00:38:56.300 --> 00:39:00.450
The same space that once
featured these illegal but

00:39:00.450 --> 00:39:04.240
often very beautiful murals done
by the teenagers of New

00:39:04.240 --> 00:39:07.460
York City, you can now buy
advertising space on these

00:39:07.460 --> 00:39:11.340
trains-- on the outsides
of these trains.

00:39:11.340 --> 00:39:14.840
For $50,000 a month, you can buy
strips of advertising that

00:39:14.840 --> 00:39:17.380
will run on the exteriors
of subway trains.

00:39:17.380 --> 00:39:21.730
So in this war over public
space, which was a coded war,

00:39:21.730 --> 00:39:23.730
which was largely a
war against young

00:39:23.730 --> 00:39:25.610
underprivileged kids--

00:39:25.610 --> 00:39:27.980
kids of color, largely--
in New York City--

00:39:27.980 --> 00:39:30.550
now, public space can be yours
if you can pay for it.

00:39:30.550 --> 00:39:33.620
And yet, the city of New York is
still so violently opposed

00:39:33.620 --> 00:39:34.250
to graffiti--

00:39:34.250 --> 00:39:36.090
even the aesthetic
of graffiti--

00:39:36.090 --> 00:39:38.460
that the one thing you can't
advertise on the outside of

00:39:38.460 --> 00:39:39.460
the train--

00:39:39.460 --> 00:39:41.720
you can't use anything
that looks--

00:39:41.720 --> 00:39:43.460
"looks" like graffiti.

00:39:43.460 --> 00:39:46.100
So you can put a naked
woman in a dog

00:39:46.100 --> 00:39:47.710
collar advertising vodka.

00:39:47.710 --> 00:39:50.990
That's cool with CBS outdoor,
which administers these ads on

00:39:50.990 --> 00:39:52.720
behalf of the MTA
and the city.

00:39:52.720 --> 00:39:56.570
You can put a placard on a bus
that is widely regarded as

00:39:56.570 --> 00:39:58.240
hate speech against
Palestinians.

00:39:58.240 --> 00:39:59.980
That got through.

00:39:59.980 --> 00:40:02.570
But when I tried to advertise
this book--

00:40:02.570 --> 00:40:04.370
and to be fair, I knew they
were going to say no.

00:40:04.370 --> 00:40:08.460
I didn't have $50,000 to spend
on no damn train--

00:40:08.460 --> 00:40:12.010
they rejected the advertising,
because

00:40:12.010 --> 00:40:13.790
it looked like graffiti.

00:40:13.790 --> 00:40:16.090
And to me, this is where the
sort of intellectual

00:40:16.090 --> 00:40:20.900
bankruptcy of the policy becomes
clear, because the MTA

00:40:20.900 --> 00:40:24.360
and the City of New York define
graffiti as vandalism.

00:40:24.360 --> 00:40:26.850
They define it as the defacement
of property through

00:40:26.850 --> 00:40:27.900
a list of means.

00:40:27.900 --> 00:40:31.430
A litany of ways.

00:40:31.430 --> 00:40:35.030
What I'm proposing to do on this
train is not vandalism.

00:40:35.030 --> 00:40:36.210
It's advertising.

00:40:36.210 --> 00:40:38.940
And yet, the aesthetic is
being-- so it's the

00:40:38.940 --> 00:40:43.150
criminalization now not of an
action, but of an aesthetic.

00:40:43.150 --> 00:40:46.290
So to tell me that I can't put
graffiti style letters on the

00:40:46.290 --> 00:40:49.725
train, there's no real legal or
intellectual basis for it.

00:40:49.725 --> 00:40:53.490
A graffiti style letter, in this
context, is kind of like

00:40:53.490 --> 00:40:56.690
a robbery style purchase.

00:40:56.690 --> 00:40:58.550
It doesn't actually
make sense.

00:40:58.550 --> 00:41:00.890
But this war was never
about aesthetics.

00:41:00.890 --> 00:41:03.560
It was about public space and
who had access to it.

00:41:03.560 --> 00:41:05.800
So what I try to do in the book,
which I don't have time

00:41:05.800 --> 00:41:11.750
to read from, unfortunately,
is deal with the return of

00:41:11.750 --> 00:41:14.340
these writers from the '70s
and '80s who have been

00:41:14.340 --> 00:41:17.490
marginalized, who have
disappeared because the thing

00:41:17.490 --> 00:41:21.040
they invented they have now
paradoxically outlived.

00:41:21.040 --> 00:41:23.760
Graffiti has become a worldwide
phenomenon, but it

00:41:23.760 --> 00:41:26.620
no longer exists in the vibrant,
original form that it

00:41:26.620 --> 00:41:28.810
once did in their own city.

00:41:28.810 --> 00:41:31.570
And the story is told by the
son of two famous writers.

00:41:31.570 --> 00:41:33.690
He's an 18-year-old
kid named Dondi.

00:41:33.690 --> 00:41:36.240
He's recently been kicked out
of his prestigious Manhattan

00:41:36.240 --> 00:41:38.540
prep school for selling
marijuana--

00:41:38.540 --> 00:41:41.100
a prep school he refers to
throughout the book only as

00:41:41.100 --> 00:41:45.540
Whoop Dee Woo, Ivy League,
We's A Comin' Academy.

00:41:45.540 --> 00:41:49.520
And through the return of his
father, who's been on the lam

00:41:49.520 --> 00:41:52.890
for 16 years, and the
reassemblage of his father's

00:41:52.890 --> 00:41:56.370
shattered graffiti crew, and
some minor incidents of time

00:41:56.370 --> 00:42:00.720
travel and some possible demons
who may or may not live

00:42:00.720 --> 00:42:03.260
deep within the bowels of
the tunnel system--

00:42:03.260 --> 00:42:06.320
New York's tunnel system goes 18
levels deep in some places,

00:42:06.320 --> 00:42:08.090
so there are a lot of
unused tunnels.

00:42:08.090 --> 00:42:10.180
There are people living in
those tunnels-- the mole

00:42:10.180 --> 00:42:12.180
people, they're sometimes
known as-- they make an

00:42:12.180 --> 00:42:13.830
appearance in here as well.

00:42:13.830 --> 00:42:17.130
This elaborate caper comes
together to attempt to paint

00:42:17.130 --> 00:42:21.510
every train at once, thus
affecting either a total

00:42:21.510 --> 00:42:25.030
shutdown of the MTA, which would
wreak havoc on New York,

00:42:25.030 --> 00:42:29.070
or the running, once again, of
painted trains, which is

00:42:29.070 --> 00:42:31.660
intended to bring down this
figure who's historically the

00:42:31.660 --> 00:42:33.420
enemy of these graffiti
writers.

00:42:33.420 --> 00:42:38.450
It's a book I had a lot of fun
writing, and I'll leave it at

00:42:38.450 --> 00:42:40.745
that, because I think we need
time for some Q and A, and

00:42:40.745 --> 00:42:41.660
I've been running
my mouth enough.

00:42:41.660 --> 00:42:44.870
So thank you Google, Googlers,
for having us today.

00:42:44.870 --> 00:42:46.190
We appreciate it.

00:42:46.190 --> 00:42:49.120
And if you want to buy
some books, we

00:42:49.120 --> 00:42:49.980
definitely will sign.

00:42:49.980 --> 00:42:52.180
And even if you don't, the
discount that you get is

00:42:52.180 --> 00:42:53.510
actually better than mine.

00:42:53.510 --> 00:42:57.420
So if you buy some books, I'm
happy to buy them from you at

00:42:57.420 --> 00:42:58.500
a slight markup.

00:42:58.500 --> 00:42:59.760
So we can talk about that.

