00:47:49.040 --> 00:47:51.530
AUDIENCE: Could you talk a bit
about Angry Black White Boy,

00:47:51.530 --> 00:47:53.250
if I have the name right?

00:47:53.250 --> 00:47:54.780
ADAM MANSBACH: You do, yeah.

00:47:54.780 --> 00:47:57.030
Angry Black White Boy is a
novel that I published in

00:47:57.030 --> 00:48:02.080
2005, and it was kind of my
attempt to remix the American

00:48:02.080 --> 00:48:05.610
race novel for the hip
hop generation.

00:48:05.610 --> 00:48:09.060
As I said earlier, as that MC
Hammer anecdote perhaps

00:48:09.060 --> 00:48:11.290
illustrated, I've been involved
and invested in hip

00:48:11.290 --> 00:48:12.890
hop for a long time.

00:48:12.890 --> 00:48:15.560
And at the time that I got into
it in the late '80s, it

00:48:15.560 --> 00:48:17.790
was really one of the only sites
in American life where

00:48:17.790 --> 00:48:20.710
whiteness was made subjective--
where as a white

00:48:20.710 --> 00:48:23.000
person, you had to really think
critically about race

00:48:23.000 --> 00:48:24.090
and privilege.

00:48:24.090 --> 00:48:27.080
So Angry Black White
Boy is a satire.

00:48:27.080 --> 00:48:31.060
It's the story of an Afrocentric
white kid named

00:48:31.060 --> 00:48:35.630
Macon Detornay who is kind of
politicized by the music he

00:48:35.630 --> 00:48:38.580
grows up listening to-- the era
of Public Enemy and X Clan

00:48:38.580 --> 00:48:40.280
and Boogie Down Productions--

00:48:40.280 --> 00:48:45.970
and develops a rather profound
or extreme critique of white

00:48:45.970 --> 00:48:50.730
privilege in America, and ends
up acting on that as a New

00:48:50.730 --> 00:48:51.830
York City cab driver.

00:48:51.830 --> 00:48:55.900
He begins robbing other white
people who get in his cab,

00:48:55.900 --> 00:48:59.610
which leads to a manhunt for
the presumably black cab

00:48:59.610 --> 00:49:01.980
driver who's sticking up
all these white people.

00:49:01.980 --> 00:49:05.820
He ends up becoming kind of an
infamous celebrity once he's

00:49:05.820 --> 00:49:10.710
apprehended, and uses his new
found platform to call for a

00:49:10.710 --> 00:49:15.340
national day of apology, based
on a rhetorical statement in

00:49:15.340 --> 00:49:16.620
Malcolm X's autobiography.

00:49:16.620 --> 00:49:19.800
Malcolm says, the nature of
racism in this country is so

00:49:19.800 --> 00:49:24.530
pernicious, so persistent, so
unavoidable, and benefits

00:49:24.530 --> 00:49:26.270
white people every day of their
lives, that they should

00:49:26.270 --> 00:49:28.160
really be walking up to black
folks on the street and

00:49:28.160 --> 00:49:29.540
apologizing.

00:49:29.540 --> 00:49:32.420
Now, this is a rhetorical
statement in Malcolm's book.

00:49:32.420 --> 00:49:35.400
Macon is like, we're going to
do this shit on Friday.

00:49:35.400 --> 00:49:37.790
So people from all over the
country go to New York to

00:49:37.790 --> 00:49:41.860
participate in this well
intentioned and ill considered

00:49:41.860 --> 00:49:44.460
and ultimately disastrous day of
apology, and things kind of

00:49:44.460 --> 00:49:45.984
take off from there.

